data.content:
Your project targets **net10.0**, so the best approach for file system statics is the **`System.IO.Abstractions`** NuGet package — it's battle-tested and covers `File.*`, `Directory.*`, and `Path.*` out of the box. No need to write a custom wrapper.

### 1. Install the package

```bash
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions
```

### 2. Inject `IFileSystem` instead of calling statics

Refactor `ReportGenerator` to accept `IFileSystem` via constructor injection:

```csharp
using System.IO.Abstractions;

namespace NeedsWrappers.Services;

public class ReportGenerator(IFileSystem fileSystem)
{
    public string GenerateReport(string reportName)
    {
        var timestamp = DateTime.UtcNow.ToString("yyyyMMdd_HHmmss");
        var outputDir = Environment.GetEnvironmentVariable("REPORT_OUTPUT_DIR") ?? "/tmp/reports";

        if (!fileSystem.Directory.Exists(outputDir))
        {
            fileSystem.Directory.CreateDirectory(outputDir);
        }

        var reportPath = fileSystem.Path.Combine(outputDir, $"{reportName}_{timestamp}.txt");
        var content = $"Report: {reportName}\nGenerated: {DateTime.UtcNow:O}\nMachine: {Environment.MachineName}";

        fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(reportPath, content);
        Console.WriteLine($"Report written to {reportPath}");

        return reportPath;
    }
}
```

The mapping is straightforward — every static becomes a member on the injected `fileSystem`:

| Before (static) | After (injected) |
|---|---|
| `File.ReadAllText(...)` | `fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(...)` |
| `File.WriteAllText(...)` | `fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(...)` |
| `Directory.Exists(...)` | `fileSystem.Directory.Exists(...)` |
| `Path.Combine(...)` | `fileSystem.Path.Combine(...)` |

### 3. Register in DI

```csharp
// In Program.cs or wherever you configure services:
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

### 4. Test with `MockFileSystem`

Install the test helper in your test project:

```bash
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers
```

Then write tests with a fully in-memory file system:

```csharp
using System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers;

var mockFs = new MockFileSystem();
mockFs.AddDirectory("/tmp/reports");

var generator = new ReportGenerator(mockFs);
var path = generator.GenerateReport("sales");

Assert.True(mockFs.File.Exists(path));
Assert.Contains("Report: sales", mockFs.File.ReadAllText(path));
```

No files touch disk, tests run fast, and you can pre-populate directories/files as needed.

> **Bonus:** Your `ReportGenerator` also uses `DateTime.UtcNow` and `Environment.*`. On .NET 10 you can inject the built-in `TimeProvider` for time, and a small custom `IEnvironmentProvider` for environment variables — want me to generate those wrappers too?
